What is Text to Speech?

Text to Speech (TTS) is a technology that converts written text into spoken audio. 
It allows computers and web applications to read text aloud using synthetic voices. 
This technology is commonly used in accessibility tools, virtual assistants, learning applications, and productivity software.

How It Works

The application uses the browser’s built-in Web Speech API to convert text into speech.
The user enters text into the input field.
Available system voices are dynamically loaded.
The user selects a preferred voice.
The text is converted into speech using the SpeechSynthesisUtterance interface.
The speech can be controlled using pause and resume functionality.
The browser processes the text and generates audio output using the selected voice.

Technologies Used

HTML5 – Structure of the application
CSS3 – Styling and responsive design
JavaScript (ES6) – Logic and interactivity
Web Speech API – Speech synthesis functionality
DOM Manipulation & Event Handling


The Text to Speech project demonstrates practical implementation of JavaScript with real browser APIs. 
It highlights skills in frontend development, user interaction handling, and integrating native browser capabilities to build interactive web applications.
